{"cursor":"7819","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Bhil |image = |pop = |region1 = India |region2 =\nGujarat |pop2 = 3,441,945 {{cite web |url =\nhttp://www.censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/dh_st_gujarat.pdf |title =\nGujarat: Data Highlights the Scheduled Tribes| accessdate = 2008-03-31 | last =\n| first = | work = Census of India 2001 | publisher = Census Commission of India\n}} |region3 = Madhya Pradesh |pop3 = 4,619,068 |region4 =\nMaharashtra |pop4 = 1,818,792 {{cite web |url =\nhttp://www.censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/dh_st_maha.pdf| title =\nMaharashtra: Data Highlights the Scheduled Tribes| accessdate = 2008-03-31 |\nlast = | first = | work = Census of India 2001 | publisher = Census Commission\nof India }} |region5 = Rajasthan |pop5 = 2,805,948 {{cite web |url =\nhttp://www.censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/dh_st_rajasthan.pdf | title\n= Rajasthan: Data Highlights the Scheduled Tribes| accessdate = 2008-03-31 |\nlast = | first = | work = Census of India 2001 | publisher = Census Commission\nof India }} |region6 = Pakistan |pop6 = 382,000 |languages = Bhil\nlanguages |religions = |related = }}\n\n'Bhils' are primarily an Adivasi people of Central India. Bhils are also settled\nin the Tharparkar District of Sindh, Pakistan. They speak the Bhil languages, a\nsubgroup of the Western Zone of the Indo-Aryan languages.\n\nBhils are listed as Adivasi residents of the states of Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh,\nChhattisgarh, Maharashtra and Rajasthan - all in the western Deccan regions and\ncentral India - as well as in Tripura in far-eastern India, on the border with\nBangladesh. Bhils are divided into a number of endogamous territorial divisions,\nwhich in turn have a number of clans and lineages. Most Bhils now speak the\nlanguage of the region they reside in, such as Marathi and Gujarati. They mostly\nspeak a dialect of Hindi. People of India Gujarat Volume XXII Part One\nedited by R.B Lal, S.V Padmanabham & A Mohideen page 214 to 251 Popular\nPrakashan\n\nThe Ghoomar dance is one well-known aspect of Bhil culture.\n","linknr":332,"url":"Bhils","recorded":1375084498,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Bhil_people&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Bhil_people&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Bhil_people","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Bhils&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Bheel_(disambiguation)","/wiki/Bil_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:Children_in_Raisen_district,_MP,_India.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Children_in_Raisen_district%2C_MP%2C_India.jpg/210px-Children_in_Raisen_district%2C_MP%2C_India.jpg","/wiki/Gujarat","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Madhya_Pradesh","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Maharashtra","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Rajasthan","#cite_note-4","/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed","/wiki/Bhil_languages","/wiki/Adivasi","/wiki/Tharparkar_District","/wiki/Sindh","/wiki/Bhil_languages","/wiki/Indo-Aryan_languages#Western_Zone","/wiki/Indo-Aryan_languages","/wiki/Gujarat","/wiki/Madhya_Pradesh","/wiki/Chhattisgarh","/wiki/Maharashtra","/wiki/Rajasthan","/wiki/Deccan","/wiki/Tripura","/wiki/Bangladesh","/wiki/Endogamy","/wiki/Marathi_language","/wiki/Gujarati_language","#cite_note-5","/wiki/Ghoo